"The Guardian","source":"Guardian","photographer":"Graham Turner","altText":"harriet harman","height":"372","credit":"Graham Turner/Guardian","caption":"Harriet Harman needs to speak out about the claims made by the Daily Mail. Photograph: Graham Turner for the Guardian","picdarUrn":"GD*33991993","width":"620"}}]}]},{"webTitle":"Harriet Harman should never have been the target of this non-debate | Liz Kelly","webPublicationDate":"2014-02-28T09:52:03Z","sectionName":"Comment is free","sectionId":"commentisfree","id":"commentisfree/2014/feb/28/harriet-harman-non-debate-pie-nccl","fields":{"secureThumbnail":"https://static-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/2/27/1393532414849/Gay-Liberation-Front-demo-004.jpg","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/3n65c","standfirst":"In 1980 child sexual abuse wasn't on police and social workers' radars: that came later, and with it feminists' critique of PIE","hasStoryPackage":"true","lastModified":"2014-06-03T06:41:35Z","body":"<p>I have read and listened with frustration to the extraordinary ahistorical <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/feb/25/harriet-harman-regrets-employer-link-paedophile-lobbyists\" title=\"Guardian: Harriet Harman 'regrets' former employer's link to paedophile lobbyists\">non-debate about the National Council for Civil Liberties (NCCL) and Paedophile Information Exchange (PIE) in the 1970s</a>. Let me be clear from the outset that I have never supported PIE, being one among many radical feminists who were beginning to recognise child sexual abuse in the 1970s. But we knew so little then about its scale, and were debating sexologists and others who argued it was not necessarily harmful; this was not just a discourse of abusers, it was articulated in the <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kinsey_Reports\" title=\"Wikipedia: Kinsey Reports entry\">Kinsey Reports</a> and by a range of respected academics.</p><p>From a different direction, the <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gay_Liberation_Front\" title=\"Wikipedia: GLF entry\">Gay Liberation Front</a> (GLF) was struggling against widespread disgust at the existence and visibility of lesbians and gay men, not to mention routine discrimination. They saw themselves as the voice of \"sexual minorities\", and PIE cleverly attached itself to this banner, partly aided by the widespread conflation at the time of gay men with paedophilia. These were the days of gay liberation, women's liberation and, yes, children's liberation. \"Children's rights\" was an oxymoron in those times, which also created a space in which their \"right\" to sexuality could be articulated. So PIE literature at the time focused on this, and their status as a sexual minority, which in some peoples' eyes was legitimated through the alliance with GLF.</p><p>Libertarians of all political stripes were involved in these discussions. There were many unholy alliances in the debates about sexuality which appear now, 40 years later,  unfathomable. But we are reading the past through the present – through a present in which the word paedophile has become incendiary rhetoric, evoking monstrous others who have placed themselves outside the bounds of humanity. This is <a href=\"http://www.troubleandstrife.org/articles/issue-33/\" title=\"Trouble and Strife website\">why I called it a \"weasel word\" in 1996</a> – it expresses outrage at sexual abuse of children at the cost of understanding: understanding that children are abused by men that they know, men that are part of our families, communities, institutions and neighbourhoods.</p><p>Feminists began to learn about child sexual abuse in consciousness-raising groups, the first survey on the extent was <a href=\"http://books.google.co.uk/books/about/Sexually_victimized_children.html?id=fWpHAAAAMAAJ&amp;redir_esc=y\" title=\"Google books: Sexually victimized children, by David Finkelhor\">done in the US in 1979</a>, and when I began my PhD in 1980 it was not yet on the radar of social workers and police as a significant issue in the lives of children.</p><p>This is the context in which PIE and NCCL were operating. Harriet Harman has been excoriated for the position NCCL adopted on \"indecent images of children\" – but here too the times were ones where expanding sexual freedoms was an important thread in progressive politics, and a distinction made between images and actions. It was only in the late 1980s that the argument that child pornography (now known as child abuse images) was a record of abuse was accepted, and it took even longer for legislation to reflect this.</p><p>Radical feminists were among those who critiqued PIE, not in the words of a 1979 article in the Sunday People as \"the vilest men in Britain\", but through what we were learning about the harms of sexual abuse and our analysis that power relations between adults and children make all sexual contact abusive. We will never get close to addressing sexual abuse effectively, let alone preventing it, if we fail to learn from the past. This has been the wrong debate and Harriet Harman the wrong target.</p>","headline":"Harriet Harman should never have been the target of this non-debate","trailText":"<strong>Liz Kelly:</strong> In 1980 child sexual abuse wasn't on police and social workers' radars: that came later, and with it feminists' critique of PIE","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"theguardian.com","showInRelatedContent":"true","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/2/27/1393532414849/Gay-Liberation-Front-demo-004.jpg","wordcount":"556","commentable":"true","internalContentCode":"430929197","allowUgc":"false","internalOctopusCode":"8740598","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Liz Kelly","internalPageCode":"2051553","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-03-03T09:52:03Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2014/feb/28/harriet-harman-non-debate-pie-nccl","apiUrl":"http://beta.content