redit":"Rex/Rex","caption":"Gay Liberation Front demo, 1971 … ‘They saw themselves as the voice of ‘sexual minorities', and PIE cleverly attached themselves to this banner.' Photograph: Rex","picdarUrn":"GD*16130550","width":"620"}}]}]},{"webTitle":"Harriet Harman: 'This is a moment  to be seized - there's  no doubt about it'","webPublicationDate":"2009-05-29T23:01:00Z","sectionName":"Politics","sectionId":"politics","id":"politics/2009/may/30/harriet-harman-interview-politics-expenses","fields":{"standfirst":"While many ministers have gone to ground in the expenses crisis, deputy Labour leader Harriet Harman has been facing the public and feeling their rage. She's angry too, she tells Decca Aitkenhead, and rethinking everything from MP selection to proportional representation","hasStoryPackage":"false","lastModified":"2009-06-06T18:08:07Z","body":"<p><strong>The following correction was printed in the Guardian's Corrections and clarifications column, Saturday 6 June 2009.</strong></p><p>The profile below said that Labour's deputy leader, Harriet Harman, did the impossible ... \"trained as a QC\". In any case, she qualified as a solicitor</p><p><hr /></p><p>'Come over here and meet Bob,\" Harriet Harman beckons. \"He's been telling me how he feels about MPs' expenses. Tell Decca,\" she says, turning to Bob, \"what you've just been telling me.\"</p><p>Has Harman managed to find the one voter in Britain who thinks MPs have been unjustly maligned? This will be interesting, I think. </p><p>We're outside a primary school in the minister's south London constituency, where Harman is leafleting as parents drop their kids off in the morning - not canvassing, \"just making myself visible\". She does something like this at a local school most weeks, but seldom, if ever, in a more hostile public mood. Had her own expenses claims not been revealed as relatively blameless, I doubt the mums would be smiling at her. Bob isn't smiling, though, and nor is Harman as she listens.</p><p>\"I've been a Labour voter all my life,\" Bob says. \"I always vote, always have, at every election. So does my wife. And I tell you this, I won't be voting this time. We're shocked, disgusted, angry and hurt. I cannot believe what MPs have been doing. I'm so upset about it, I don't know what to do.\" </p><p>I glance across at Harman, and she is nodding. \"I'm so sorry, Bob,\" she says quietly. \"It is awful.\"</p><p>Since the revelations of expenses claims broke, many ministers have been conspicuous by their absence, but Harman has been more like a human shield, touring TV studios, absorbing the rage, struggling to maintain what's left of an election campaign in the face of Armageddon. I'd never met her, but over the years had digested an impression of a somewhat humourless, tightly wound attack dog. Here on the street, though, is someone quite unexpected - open, warm and willing to take all the anger this voter has to vent. \"It's still building up,\" she offers frankly when Bob has gone. \"It's getting more, getting worse rather than better.\"</p><p>When we meet again later that day in her Whitehall office, she says she can't remember the last time she had a day off. She should look shattered, but like a surprising number of politicians, she's better looking than she appears on TV: softer, less staring-eyed, more human. There's not a trace of the pomp of high office in the room; her aides are a Scottish former stand-up and a smiley young man in skinny jeans and trainers, and when she talks about the technical details of expenses claims, she jokes, \"Anorak on\" and mimes pulling one over her head. She plonks herself down on the sofa as if we were just here for a chat, then gets up to fetch her specs. \"If I get my glasses, my brain will operate more dynamically,\" she smiles briskly. \"Right!\"</p><p>Did she have any idea what was coming in the expenses revelations? \"Well, I ... I knew I didn't know. It's Donald Rumsfeld's known unknown. It was definitely a known unknown.\" As an inner London MP, she'd never had any dealings with the second home allowances, she stresses, and \"if there are discussions going on somewhere, where people discuss how to maximise your income by flipping or something like that, if there's a kind of network and sharing of worst practice, I've never come across it.\" </p><p>So was she shocked? \"Yeah, I have been shocked. I did think that when it came out it might be ...\" She lets the sentence fall away. \"I don't want to sit in judgment on people but, no, my imagination has not been equal to the task of anticipating. And there's still more to come out - there's the office costs, then there's the travel, so we're still in the process. I think the distrust is going to deepen.\"</p><p>She is choosing her words with care, not only, I suspect, for fear of appearing to sit in judgment. Having been one of just 10 women MPs when first elected in 1982, at seven months pregnant, she has long been a critic of the gentlemen's club culture, and while many of her colleagues are calling this crisis a catastrophe, to reformers it is also an unmistakable opportunity. Is she secretly glad that it's all come out? \"I think, um, I think it's going to be ... ultimately, I think it's going to be ... it's going to have been the spur for a very fundamental root and branch review of the allowances, and putting them on a statutory footing, and making sure the system is proof against abuse, and the system will be better, and the public will be able to have more confidence.\" </p><p>That sounds like a yes. \"I don't want to be saying this is a great opportunity,\" she says, looking uncomfortable. </p><p>But it is a great opportunity, isn't it? She hesitates for a moment. \"It is a moment to be seized, yes,\" she says softly. \"There's no doubt about it.\"</p><p>Then something surprising happens. I'd expected to have to make the argument for some radical catharsis - a lancing of the boil - before the detail of any reform can begin to be discussed, but she makes it for me. \"You can't begin to mobilise that moment, or take that opportunity, whilst the electorate are so utterly disillusioned. Until such time as the public join in with that discussion, it's not one worth having. And at the moment they don't want to be joining in. You can't even begin to have a discussion with somebody about\" - she adopts a silly voice - \"'Oh, let's renew our democracy' when they wouldn't want to talk about it to us. Bob doesn't want to be having a discussion about how you'd engage in all the wider issues, because that trust has got to be rebuilt first, before people will engage in how we can use this moment to strengthen democracy. Democracy is not for us, it's for them. And until they're prepared to have a discussion with us about how we renew democracy, there's no renewing to be done.\"</p><p>She has already announced interim expenses reforms, including a new Parliamentary Standards Authority, but the implication of what she's just said is that first something much more drastic has to happen. This is what her critics are demanding - and if she agrees with them, I can't see the argument against calling for a wholesale reselection of every single sitting MP. \"But that process is happening,\" she protests. Labour MPs whose claims have brought the party into disrepute will face a scrutiny panel, and the prospect of deselection. \"But it's not going to happen in respect of every single MP, because what's the point?\"</p><p>The point would be that if the public now think all MPs are on the make, and Harman is insisting they're not, only wholesale reselection would restore faith in the surviving MPs. \"But I'm not quite sure how it helps the public's mind for me to go through that procedure,\" she says, \"because it would just be a 'tick box' thing. What's the point?\"</p><p>In her case, I agree, it would be a short process. And across the country, any inconvenience would be modest compared with the magnitude of the crisis in trust. Like all reselected MPs, Harman would then be able to look voters in the eye, say she'd been through the same scrutiny as everyone else and proved that her hands were clean. There is a thoughtful pause. \"Hmmm,\" she says. Then, \"Mmmm. You mean, we'd get a sort of charter mark? Like Ofsted. Ofpol, it would be like Ofpol.\" </p><p>Exactly. After all, even when we know a school is excellent, Ofsted still does an inspection. \"I'll have to think about that ... But there's a whole load who've done absolutely nothing wrong. And we don't want to create a climate where we encourage the notion that everybody is under suspicion.\" </p><p>But that climate already exists. Surely it can be dispelled now only by making everyone go through that process. She thinks again. \"It might be that actually, instead of us not encouraging the notion, we're not responding to the level of reassurance people need,\" she says thoughtfully. Then she looks up at me. \"It might be that you're right.\"</p><p>The other option, of course, would be a general election. Why not just be done with it and call one? \"But there is going to be a general election within the year anyway, so I feel my responsibility as leader of the House is to work hard to sort out the system to put it on a better footing, and then all parties of the political system will be on a better footing to face the electorate and say we've cleared out the system. We've got a problem and we've got to sort it out, and I feel it's our responsibility collectively to sort out the problem.\"</p><p>But when a school is failing, the government always says get rid of the head and put in a new team, because the old one clearly doesn't know how to turn the school around. \"But this is not just an issue for the Labour party, this is an issue that has affected all parties.\" </p><p>Yes, but even though the Tories and Lib Dems are implicated, they're still calling for a general election, so why isn't she? \"If there was a big choice for the voters - here's the party that wants to clean up politics and here's the one that doesn't - then that would, you know, then that would - I mean - I think that when the ...\" She breaks off, looking less than convinced by her own words. \"There will be a general election within a year,\" she begins again more firmly, \"but I think really our task is to sort out the problem, and not throw everything up into the air and say, right, let's call an election. I'm absolutely convinced that our responsibility is to sort the situation out, definitely.\"</p><p>It's such a bafflingly weak argument that it can't be what she really means. Isn't the worry that voter turnout would be so low that whoever won would have a pitiful mandate - yet, like all new governments, would have little enthusiasm for reforming a system that had just delivered them to office? \"Perhaps you've made an argument for sorting it out before an election.\"</p><p>But why is she not making it? \"Oh, right. Gosh. Well, it was a very good point. I was intending to make it myself, you understand,\" and we both laugh. She makes a brief note, looks up and adds: \"Actually, I think if we don't sort out the situation before the next general election, there will be a very low turnout, there's no doubt about it. And therefore we've got to win back their confidence and trust in order to make the general election something that delivers a mandate.\" </p><p>Harman is the cabinet's second longest serving MP, has served in all but three years of the Labour government, and currently holds no fewer than four jobs - deputy leader, secretary of state for women and equality, chair of the Labour party and leader of the Commons. Now 58, she trained as a QC before becoming legal officer for the National Council for Civil Liberties (now Liberty) in the late 70s, and her closest admirers include some of the brightest in cabinet, such as Ed Miliband. </p><p>Yet for years she has been dogged by the charge that she is not very bright. Frank Field famously described her as \"thick\", while to others she is too posh to be quite credible: the daughter of a Harley Street consultant and a niece of Lord Longford, she was privately educated at St Paul's Girls' School. Her decision to send her three children to selective, though state, schools enraged some Labour loyalists, and when the late Tory grandee Alan Clark was asked whom he found more attractive, Harman or Edwina Currie, he replied, \"Oh, Harriet, of course. It's simply a matter of class.\"</p><p>But in a government that has featured no shortage of millionaire men, it would be odd to single out as some sort of upper-class infidel a woman who once said she has \"never spent more than &pound;50\" on a handbag and who for 27 years has been married to the trade unionist Jack Dromey, whom she met on a picket line. </p><p>If anything has hampered Harman, it has probably been her feminism. Mocking incredulity that her first parliamentary question to Margaret Thatcher concerned after-school clubs led to lobby jokes about \"Hattie Harperson\", which continue to this day, despite, as she points out, the transition of women's concerns into mainstream politics. She once joked that, should she become prime minister, \"There aren't enough airports in the country for all the men who would want to flee\", and her equality bill currently going through parliament would give employers the right, on grounds of gender, to choose an equally qualified woman over a male candidate. The only serious contender to have categorically ruled herself out of any future leadership race, Harman has been a loyal Kinnockite, Smithite, Blairite and now Brownite, yet still a whispering campaign persists against her, and she's accused of exploiting her deputy leader's mandate to pursue some militant feminist agenda of her own. </p><p>But you don't get to be where Harman is today without sacrificing your feminism unless you are, in fact, very smart. Those critics who think she has her eye on the main job may interpret her warnings that \"things will get worse\", and her very public sympathy for Bob, as evidence of opportunistic ambition. I certainly don't find her stupid; on the contrary, what she seems to be doing is thinking - with a more open mind and greater willingness to listen than most ministers I've met, and a world away from the pointless point-scoring of a New Labour automaton. Our meeting is a rare and surprising thing - less like an interview than an exchange of ideas, an actual conversation. </p><p>For example, when I ask if she would support the addition of \"None Of The Above\" to ballot papers, at first she says we already have that option by abstaining. \"None Of The Above is not voting.\" </p><p>But not voting could mean anything; it could mean I forgot to vote, or couldn't get to the polls, whereas None Of The Above is an unambiguous democratic expression, currently unavailable to the electorate. \"Mmmm,\" she murmurs. \"Bob did say he'd vote for None Of The Above if he could.\" </p><p>Politicians rarely quote anyone who disagrees with them, yet Harman repeatedly invokes Bob, regardless of how critical his comments. Bob is practically turning into our own Joe the Plumber - \"You'd better change his name,\" she says (I have), \"or the poor man will have the press all over him.\" But whereas John McCain kept quoting Joe's attack on Barack Obama, this is more like Obama invoking Joe's criticisms himself. Harman's thinking on reform does seem remarkably fluid: when she describes it as an \"ongoing situation\", she means it. \"I don't think,\" she admits, \"I've made up my mind about this None Of The Above question.\" She smiles: \"Am I allowed to have 'Neither Of The Above' - neither yes nor no?\" Would she support Alan Johnson's call for a referendum on proportional representation? \"Well, I do think that the public preparedness to think about these things is much more than it was. There's a whole load of things that have got their moment in the sun now, from changing the hours of the House to all the issues around the electoral system.\" So would she back Johnson's idea in cabinet? \"I would be more positive than negative,\" she says. So, in principle, she would not oppose it? \"No.\"</p><p>When Harman is unforthcoming, it is usually with reason. She won't comment on whether Michael Martin should receive the customary peerage conferred on a former speaker, nor for whom she will vote to replace him, because, \"as leader of the House, I'm just not going to do that.\" When I suggest that, despite the monstrous extravagance of many Tory expenses claims, the crisis is playing well for David Cameron, she says, \"You know, how it plays for him, we'll just have to leave to him. I'm averse to the notion of 'playing' this any way at all. If Bob felt I was playing this, that would be the final, final straw. So my approach has not been to play politics with all of this.\"</p><p>But voters seem to approve of Cameron's angry condemnation of colleagues. His actions may have been high-handed - \"Or about wanting,\" she interjects, \"to get rid of a load of his MPs because they never liked him and he never liked them\" - yet they're still being interpreted as strong leadership. \"There is a process in the Labour party, which is one that involves an element of natural justice,\" she counters firmly, \"which is that if allegations are made, people are entitled to have their say about whether or not the facts that have been put there are wrong. Natural justice and fairness can sometimes fall victim when there's a great sense of anxiety, and I'm not going to contribute to that.\"</p><p>Her defence of the Commons' tardiness in publishing all expenses claims is less convincing. Over and again, she insists it takes time to remove private details such as credit card numbers. \"I know it sounds hopelessly bureaucratic,\" she says - and frankly, it does: if the Telegraph can manage it, why can't the government? \"Well, yes, I know there has been tremendous frustration among members about why the house authorities are letting the Telegraph set the agenda.\" Does she share it? She looks awkward. \"I've got a kind of collective responsibility for that, so it's not for me to say I'd have liked to have done it earlier. But, yes, it should have been brought further forward still.\"</p><p>Earlier this week, the Telegraph reported that Harman claimed thousands for a media trainer. \"It wasn't like sitting me in front of a video camera and teaching me how to answer questions,\" she says, sounding unruffled. \"So although she is a media trainer, that doesn't actually describe what she did for me. She would edit newsletters I'd written, or annual reports, and comment on speeches I'd drafted, because I didn't have someone in the office to do that. But I didn't need someone to do these things on a full-time basis.\"</p><p>Would it be acceptable for other MPs to spend public money on private media training? \"I think that being an MP is about your commitment and the cause. It's not a technique. So, no, not really.\"</p><p>What she will not do, however, is condemn her colleagues. When I ask if she agrees with Gordon Brown that Hazel Blears's behaviour was \"totally unacceptable\", she says, \"I am not going to make pronouncements about cabinet members or any other MPs.\" She does not budge. \"I'm absolutely not going to sit in judgment on my colleagues.\"</p><p>She does, however, correct me when I say I understand that she won't pass judgment on them. \"No,\" she says, \"won't sit in judgment.\" What's the difference? \"We all make judgments. Everybody's making judgments all the time. But I'm deputy leader, so I'm not going to take myself to be judge and jury, because that's not what I was elected to do.\" So she wouldn't want voters to think she doesn't have opinions about what her colleagues have done? \"No,\" she says pointedly, \"I want voters to think I'm not sharing them.\"</p><p>Without naming names, then, does she feel angry with individuals who've abused the system? She pauses for so long that I later time the silence on the tape: it stretches to eight seconds. \"Well ...\" She pauses for another three, looking anguished. \"I don't think the public will be reassured that, oooh, Harriet's really angry.\"</p><p>Really? When people are angry, surely what they want first, more than anything, is to know their feelings are shared. The silence that follows lasts another eight seconds. Surely, I try again, the people we met at the school gates would feel reassured to know she feels exactly the same way as they do? \"No, I think I'm dismayed.\" </p><p>Why not angry? \"Because we can't have an angry competition - 'I'm more angry than you are! You think you're angry? Hey, I'm here to tell you I'm more angry!' - because that will not produce any results.\" It hasn't worked badly for Cameron, I say. \"Well, you can ask David Cameron about David Cameron,\" she retorts testily, suddenly looking exhausted. \"I'm more interested in sorting it out.\" </p><p>My hunch, I say, is that she's flaming mad with colleagues who've ripped us off. \"Mmm,\" she says quietly. \"Mmm.\" Then, in a low, almost inaudible voice, she says, \"Well, yes, perhaps I am angry.</p>","headline":"'This is a moment  to be seized - there's  no doubt about it'","trailText":"<p>Deputy Labour leader Harriet Harman has been facing the public and feeling their rage over the expenses crisis. She's angry too, she tells <strong>Decca Aitkenhead</strong></p>","newspaperPageNumber":"14","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"The Guardian","showInRelatedContent":"true","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/282nf","wordcount":"3510","commentable":"false","internalContentCode":"348037555","allowUgc":"false","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Decca Aitkenhead","newspaperEditionDate":"2009-05-30T00:00:00Z","internalPageCode":"1222440","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","co