mment is free","sectionId":"commentisfree","id":"commentisfree/2010/jun/20/now-put-away-diamante-fairy-wands","fields":{"standfirst":"As the No 10 drinks party showed, the political battle over sexual politics is won. Yet the cultural battle is far from over","hasStoryPackage":"false","lastModified":"2014-05-19T23:21:02Z","body":"<p>The lawns were rather gorgeous and so were most of the guests: the sun sparkled, cabinet ministers murmured and the prime minister flirted with the Liberal Democrat man he now calls his civil partner. Is this how gay liberation was supposed to end? Not with a barricade, but a drinks party, nibbling canapes on a summer evening in the garden of No 10. A Conservative prime minister held an official event for lesbian, bisexual, gay and transgender Britain and the <a href=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1287174/Cameron-welcomes-gay-celebrities-Number-10.html\" title=\"\">Daily Mail struggled to be shocked</a>.</p><p>The ordinariness of it all confirmed a wonderful thing: the country's very rapid and far-reaching acceptance of sexual difference with little of the religious and cultural hysteria that has accompanied the struggle in, for instance, the US. Nothing felt forced about last week's event – just a routine June political reception at which the majority of guests happened to be gay or lesbian.</p><p>The Labour party, Conservatives should never forget, did much of the legislative hard work that got us here. Liberals, too, were prominent in the early campaigns. Gordon Brown welcomed gay and lesbian people into Downing Street. But now no single party can claim a stranglehold on virtue. We have reached a point where an individual's sexuality does not make them more or less welcome in one party or another. You no longer have to vote Labour or Lib Dem just because you are gay, out of gratitude for reforms or fear of what a Tory government might do.</p><p>David Cameron's ostentatious detoxification has touched on cringeworthy – we can take \"pride in pride, as well as pride in our football team\", he told his guests the other day. But the changes he has brought are real and well-meant. It is easy to play a game of match-the-voting-record-to-the-rhetoric and question Cameron's authenticity, and more so that of some members of his cabinet. The <a href=\"http://www.dwp.gov.uk/\" title=\"\">Department for Work and Pensions</a> is already becoming known as the Department for Worship and Prayer, so strong are the Christian underpinnings of its ministerial team. But Cameron admits he was wrong, and that his views have changed and we should accept that.</p><p>It is worth noting in passing that the Conservative record is not all bad and Labour's not all good. <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/LGBT_rights_in_the_United_Kingdom\" title=\"\">John Major cut the age of consent from 21</a>. Tony Blair appointed a member of Opus Dei as the <a href=\"http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/is-homosexuality-a-sin-minister-for-equality-refuses-to-rule-it-out-477554.html\" title=\"\">equalities minister</a>. This year <a href=\"http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/8582868.stm\" title=\"\">Harriet Harman lobbied to stop the Equalities Act being amended to allow civil partnership ceremonies</a> to take place in religious institutions, least her law fall foul of cantankerous bishops. Meanwhile Chris Grayling, who expressed the <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2010/apr/03/tory-tape-gays-bed-breakfast\" title=\"\">foolish but intellectually defensible position that the owners of private guest houses should be able to deny gay couples a bed</a>, found himself demoted several rungs down the ministerial ladder.</p><p>But overall this is an issue Labour got right, as the Conservative <a href=\"http://www.nickboles.com/\" title=\"\">MP Nick Boles</a> said in a generous maiden speech the other day. \"I would not be standing here today if they had not passed legislation to extend full equality and respect to everyone in Britain – and thereby entrench a change in culture and attitudes that my own party has now embraced. This was the Labour party at its best: brave, principled and humane.\"</p><p>The political battle is won – though the cultural one is far from over. We are running out of laws that need to be changed. This is the moment to pack away the pink fake fur tutus and the diamante fairy wands. Group identity is more than anything a product of repression. The fact that someone is gay or lesbian need no longer be their primary defining characteristic: it can be in the background or foreground as they choose, part of their genetic identity.</p><p>So I suppose I should welcome the fact that Stonewall's chief executive, <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/2010/may/30/david-laws-homosexuality-parliamentary-expenses\" title=\"\">Ben Summerskill, turned on David Laws in print</a>. \"How can anyone 'represent' a community of interest if they're unable ever to admit they belong to it and can speak of their own lived experience?\" Summerskill asked. He thinks that we have reached a point where everyone in politics should find it possible to come out and yet everyone who is out should be duty-bound to define themselves prominently by their sexuality.</p><p>I think he is wrong on both points and that Laws got himself into a mess primarily because he was gay and not because he was greedy. Laws never asked to represent any community other than his Yeovil constituency. Yet those, like me, who found Summerskill's criticisms of Laws ill-judged and partisan, might reflect that we have achieved a sort of maturity when the leading gay rights group no longer feels the need to defend a minister whose sexuality is splashed all over the papers. Leftwing gay men can now disagree with rightwing gay men without any threat to a shared cause.</p><p>Discrimination remains: gay men cannot give blood. The national church remains a bastion of unequal treatment. Homophobic bullying is common in schools. YouGov polling found one in eight lesbian, gay and bisexual adults are victims of homophobic incidents each year. In arguing that the political battle is won I don't mean to suggest everything is perfect. But other elements in society, less articulate, less well-connected, perhaps not courted by politicians, suffer worse discrimination now. So thanks for the white wine, prime minister, but it's time we were moving on.</p>","headline":"This is the moment to pack away the diamante wands","trailText":"<strong>Julian Glover:</strong> As the No 10 drinks party showed, the political battle over sexual politics is won. Yet the cultural battle is far from over","newspaperPageNumber":"28","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"The Guardian","showInRelatedContent":"true","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/2hzcy","wordcount":"886","commentable":"true","internalContentCode":"363955113","allowUgc":"false","internalOctopusCode":"3499415","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Julian Glover","newspaperEditionDate":"2010-06-21T00:00:00Z","internalPageCode":"1415334","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2010-06-23T19:29:05Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2010/jun/20/now-put-away-diamante-fairy-wands","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/commentisfree/2010/jun/20/now-put-away-diamante-fairy-wands","tags":[{"id":"commentisfree/commentisfree","webTitle":"Comment is free","type":"blog","sectionId":"commentisfree","sectionName":"Comment is free","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/commentisfree","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/commentisfree/commentisfree","references":[]},{"id":"profile/julianglover","webTitle":"Julian Glover","rcsId":"GNL004681","r2ContributorId":"15925","bylineImageUrl":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/contributor/2007/09/28/julian_glover_140x140.jpg","type":"contributor","bio":"<p>Julian Glover, a former Guardian commentator, is a speechwriter for David 