 is, a violinist in the London Symphony Orchestra.</p><p>Harman's not afraid of political knockabout, and of course she is fantastically experienced, so it will be&nbsp;interesting to see how she tackles culture secretary <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/jeremy-hunt\" title=\"\">Jeremy Hunt</a> head-on. Finally, the consistent thread through her career has been her feminism: and frankly, we just can't have enough of that in the arts. Or anywhere, for that matter.</p><p></p><h2>Bad smells in California</h2><p>A mole from <strong>San Francisco Opera</strong> has passed me a memo&nbsp;sent around the company. \"Dear&nbsp;Artists &amp; Staff,\" it begins. \"PLEASE REFRAIN FROM WEARING ANY TYPE OF FRAGRANCE (PERFUME, STRONG HAIR SPRAY, SHAVING COLOGNE, ETC.) AT ANY REHEARSAL OR PERFORMANCE. Many people are allergic to fragrant products; this allergy can prove damaging to the singer's vocal cords, not to mention the miserable symptoms. We are often all in very close proximity and it is very important that we all take the time to be thoughtful and considerate regarding the use of fragrances.\" You can just <em>tell</em> there's some madly prima-donnaish singer behind this. They'll have only themselves to blame when they have to inhale Eau de Sweaty Tenor, unleavened by a hint of Chanel.</p><h2>Fiennes in art-world spoof</h2><p><strong>Elmgreen and Dragset </strong>entertained visitors to the 2009 Venice Biennale with their mordant work <a href=\"http://vernissage.tv/blog/2009/06/19/elmgreen-dragset-the-collectors-at-venice-biennial-2009-interview-with-ingar-dragset/\" title=\"\">The Collectors</a>, which saw the Nordic and Danish pavilions transformed into art aficionados' homes, one of which featured a dead collector face-down in his pool. The Scandinavian duo have now written a play, Happy Days in the Art World, starring <strong>Joseph Fiennes</strong>, Charles Edwards and Kim Criswell.</p><p>It is, says Michael Elmgreen, a Beckettian (big clue in the title) look at&nbsp;their own existence, \"with biographical stuff from our lives as well as a lot of lies\". The main characters will, says&nbsp;Elmgreen, be \"cynical and humorous and it will be very unflattering; if the play also makes&nbsp;fun of others, it certainly makes more fun of ourselves\". It&nbsp;opens in New York next month, at the Skirball Centre for the Performing Arts. There are also two&nbsp;preview performances at Glasgow's Tramway on Friday and Saturday next week.</p>","headline":"This week's arts diary","trailText":"Harman grabs shadow-culture post, plus a whiff of San Francisco Opera, and Fiennes in art-world spoof","newspaperPageNumber":"23","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"The Guardian","showInRelatedContent":"true","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/32h5e","wordcount":"492","commentable":"true","internalContentCode":"380257948","allowUgc":"false","internalOctopusCode":"5316365","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Charlotte Higgins","newspaperEditionDate":"2011-10-12T00:00:00Z","internalPageCode":"1646231","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2011-10-14T21:30:02Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/culture/charlottehigginsblog/2011/oct/11/arts-diary","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/culture/charlottehigginsblog/2011/oct/11/arts-diary","tags":[{"id":"culture/series/artsdiary","webTitle":"Arts diary","description":"The week's most intriguing arts happenings","type":"series","sectionId":"culture","sectionName":"Culture","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/culture/series/artsdiary","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/culture/series/artsdiary","references":[]},{"id":"culture/charlottehigginsblog","webTitle":"Charlotte Higgins on culture","description":"Charlotte Higgins tours the UK and blogs on the latest developments in the arts, classical music, theatre and books","type":"blog","sectionId":"culture","sectionName":"Culture","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/culture/charlottehigginsblog"