 fortune. I've been very lucky indeed – I'm still on my first marriage.</p><p><strong>It is completely untrue</strong> that you can't do anything when you're not in government. You can still speak up for people's hopes and fears and you can make change happen. Look at what happened when Ed Miliband challenged Rupert Murdoch on phone hacking.</p><p><strong>You learn more from failure</strong> than you ever learn from success. My friend  Anna Coote told me that when I was sacked from the Cabinet. It also helps to think about what you want to do next and not what you have done already.</p><p><strong>I'm sure nobody wants to know this,</strong> but my husband does all the cleaning – rather too much cleaning. It is too clean, the house!</p><p><strong>There's going to be a new generation of healthy older people,</strong> hopefully. Watch out for the \"wellderly\"! Oddly, I don't mind getting old at all.</p><p><strong>Would I go back in time?</strong> Not as a woman. All those unwanted pregnancies  and women having to defer to men? No thanks.</p><p><strong>I was once caught speeding</strong> in my own constituency when I was Solicitor General. If I had not pleaded guilty I would have had to resign as I'd have been prosecuting myself! Now that's an odd situation. When the policeman showed me the speed gun there was no doubt about it: I pleaded guilty.</p><p><strong>The weekends are what I look forward to.</strong> It's when all the family come round to the house and I cook up a storm.</p><p> <em>Harriet Harman is taking part in Cancer Research UK's </em>Turn The Tables <em>(</em><a href=\"http://www.cancerresearchuk.org/\" title=\"\"><em>cancerresearchuk.org</em></a><em>)</em></p>","headline":"This much I know: Harriet Harman","trailText":"<strong>Toby Helm:</strong> The shadow secretary of state for culture, media and sport on learning from failure and not taking no for an answer","newspaperPageNumber":"8","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"The Observer","showInRel