r cabinet reshuffles.</p><p>\"I think what is important about getting rid of the old system of shadow cabinet elections within the Labour party … it was a way of the Labour party looking inwards at itself. What we have been doing at this conference this week is looking outwards to the public, and that's the most important thing of all.\"</p><p>Harman told the conference: \"This week has been a turning point. Ed [Miliband] has shown his bold and optimistic vision for the future. We've challenged the unspoken orthodoxies that have governed Britain for too long, and we've refounded our party so we can be the force that changes people's lives. Conference – let's go for it.\"</p><p>Referring to the comments by Miliband and the shadow chancellor, Ed Balls, who conceded mistakes had been made by Labour when in power, she said: \"The two Eds both acknowledged what we all know: that not everything we did in government turned out right.</p><p>\"People need to know that, over the past year, we've taken a hard look at what we did, and we've learned lessons. But it's time now to move on because we've got important work to do.\"</p><p>Hilary Benn, the shadow Commons Speaker, set out some of the strong decisions made by Labour in power. Labour had held its hands up about getting it wrong on banking regulation, he said, but made the \"right choice\" when it decided to part-nationalise some of the big banks when the system was on the point of collapse.</p><p>\"George Osborne used to complain not that we weren't doing enough on the banks but that we were being too tough on them,\" he said. \"He was wrong, and we'll take no lectures from him.\"</p><p>Benn told how he broke the news of the Northern Rock nationalisation to his father, the veteran leftwinger Tony Benn, saying: \"I rang my father up and said: 'Dad, you know you were always saying that we should nationalise the banks? Well, I've got some news for you.'\"</p><p></p><p>Harman rounded on government plans to introduce voluntary voter registration and put an end to households signing up, shifting the onus on to each individual to fill out the electoral forms.</p><p>She told delegates that the Lib Dems, \"to their eternal shame\", were \"colluding\" in the plans.</p><p>Ministers have unexpectedly proposed that it should no longer be compulsory to co-operate with electoral registration officers (EROs) when they try to compile an accurate register – in effect downgrading the civic duty to engage with politics.</p><p>The Electoral Commission, electoral administrators and psephologists have warned that as many as 10 million voters – predominantly poor, young or black and more liable to vote Labour – could fall off the electoral register as a result.</p><p>Harman said: \"The Tories hope it will help them win the election. This is a shameful assault on people's democratic right, and we will expose it and campaign against it. Parliament has no right to take away people's right to vote. The government cannot be allowed to get away with it.\"</p><p>Looking to the year ahead, Harman told activists Labour had important work to do in defending services such as Sure Start children's centres from closure, opposing the abolition of the 50p top rate of tax and defending the NHS.</p><p>She dismissed Lib Dem claims that they were acting as a brake on the Conservatives in coalition, saying they were instead being used to do the \"dirty work\".</p><p>Citing tuition fee rises, police cuts and the VAT rise, she added: \"Clearly, the brakes failed.\"</p><p>She highlighted the announcement of job losses at BAE Systems to accuse the Tories of being a party out of touch, saying Miliband was the only leader to understand people's fears in the current climate.</p><p>\"Behind their front doors, people are worried,\" she said. \"Behind the front door of Downing Street, the Tories are oblivious. It's not going to affect them – so it doesn't matter. They're so removed from people's lives.</p><p>\"But I do hear that they do watch TV from time to time and I hear they love Downtown Abbey. The only problem is they think it's a fly on the wall documentary.\"</p><p>Earlier in the day, Yvette Cooper, the shadow equalities minister, told delegates that women affected by government cuts would get \"angrier and angrier and louder and louder\".</p><p>Referring to David Cameron's <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/2011/apr/27/david-cameron-calm-down-dear\" title=\"\">calm down, dear\"</a> jibe to the shadow chief secretary to the Treasury, Angela Eagle, during a Commons exchange, Cooper said the prime minister had showed his true feelings to women concerned about the coalition's deficit reduction strategy.</p><p>\"What was David Cameron's response to women who warned him about the damage he was doing? To Harriet Harman, to Caroline Flint, to Angela Eagle? Not 'sorry', but 'Calm down dear'.</p><p>\"I think David Cameron will learn that women across the country are not going to calm down. In fact, they are getting angrier and angrier and louder and louder, and they will continue to do so until this Tory-led government drops their deeply unfair plans to turn their back on women.\"</p><p>Delegates applauded as a Liberal Democrat from Liverpool city council took the stage to announce her decision to defect to Labour.</p><p>Lynnie Hinnigan, a community activist, youth worker and parent, said she was not crossing the floor as a career move at the Labour-run council, but because, as a Lib Dem, she \"cannot defend the indefensible\".</p><p>As a mother with aspirations for her children to go to university, she said she felt betrayed by Nick Clegg over tuition fees as well as cuts to services such as Sure Start centres.</p><p>\"I spend day in, day out, trying to raise the aspirations of young people, and the reason I am coming to Labour is because Labour cares,\" she said. \"Nick Clegg lied to me, he lied to the people of Liverpool, and it's wrong.\"</p>","headline":"Harriet Harman: this week h