-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/7/9/1404924523497/Harriet-Harman-006.jpg","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/3qzgv","standfirst":"The fourth wave of feminism, from Caitlin Moran to Kimberlé Crenshaw, has energised young people, but now it needs to attack our political establishment","hasStoryPackage":"true","lastModified":"2014-07-24T15:00:42Z","body":"<p>\"What did you do in the war, Mummy? The great feminist war.\" \"I stood there on the shore and let the waves crash over me one after another, watching them build, feeling them pull me close. Waiting for the break.\"</p><p>Actually, I don't have to imagine any such conversation: as ever, the reality is rather dull. My older daughters used to come home from school all grumpy about having to \"do\" feminism. For their homework they would want me to tick one of the multiple-choice boxes explaining my exact kind of feminism. Was I, they impatiently asked, a radical or socialist or separatist feminist? \"Don't be daft,\" I would say, but homework is&nbsp;homework.</p><p>Explaining that it was never like that just annoyed them. And I feel much the same when I&nbsp;read about the waves of feminism. We are on the <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/dec/10/fourth-wave-feminism-rebel-women\" title=\"\">fourth wave</a> apparently. Grab a bodyboard! For of course, feminism contains multitudes (bickering multitudes, I concede) of thought, ideas and activism. Feminism is always a process, not a finished product: a system of ideas about gender equality that mutate and regenerate.</p><p>There are days when we can be optimistic: the <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/series/laura-bates-on-everyday-sexism\" title=\"\">discussions around everyday sexism</a>; <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/theobserver/2011/jun/19/caitlin-moran-feminism-interview\" title=\"\">Caitlin Moran's wisecracks</a> have turned her into a rock star worshipped by young girls; <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/profile/laurie-penny\" title=\"\">Laurie Penny</a>, a knowingly troublesome writer, has punched her way through the cybersphere, by turning anxiety into anger. <a href=\"http://www.newstatesman.com/lifestyle/2014/04/kimberl-crenshaw-intersectionality-i-wanted-come-everyday-metaphor-anyone-could\" title=\"\">Kimberlé Crenshaw</a> packs out lecture halls as she explains that \"intersectionality\" is not new, that we need to see race and class as intertwined and throws down the challenge to white feminists: who has the power to end debate, to walk away? That same challenge is there too from trans activists and sex workers and this is how feminism remakes itself. All of this is happening now, a consciousness raising, that seems rude and healthy and almost a movement. Almost.</p><p>Where can this energy go next? Both Moran's and Penny's revolution appears to involve dismantling neo-liberalism and an enormous amount of wanking. It's irresistible and it is bliss to be alive with such joy and rage flying round. To be middle-aged though is not very heaven, it is to have come down a bit.</p><p>For while I wait for the revolution, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/jul/08/harriet-harman-gordon-brown-inequality-labour-sexism\" title=\"\">Harriet Harman tours the TV studios</a> explaining how even at the top of politics she has been dissed and dismissed for being a woman, not given the job she was elected to do (deputy PM) by Gordon Brown. Damian McBride, Brown's former adviser, tells us that the PM was not&nbsp;sexist.</p><p>Oh frabjous day! Men get to decide who is sexist or not! Harman is then also dismissed for narcissism and ambition – attributes that appear to be valued in male politicians – but her general points on the lack of women at the top in party politics remain salient.</p><p>How have we got to this? A feminism that is culturally buzzing and politicising young women but not in any way that includes the established institutions that are perceived to be broken and decrepit? But the false doctrine of austerity has meant that women, single mothers in particular, and public sector workers in general, have been at the frontline of this war. They have been demonised and subject to punitive cuts. Even though Iain Duncan Smith's plans for Universal Credit are in tatters, have wasted a fortune and are still not signed off, his fundamentalist ideology is still in play, for it is central to Conservatism.</p><p>Squaring this circle between vibrant, hopeful feminist thought and the traditional sphere of politics is ever more difficult. But the more that politics pulls away from culture as it is lived, the more it loses its mandate. Equally, cultural theorists cannot ignore the archaic institutions, as much as we may want to.</p><p>If we take some of the basic tenets of feminism to be about equal pay or reproductive rights, we see that enshrining these in law is still part of the battle. It is noble that the 1967 Abortion Act happened not because those who supported it thought it was a vote-winner, but because they felt they had a moral duty to stop women dying.</p><p>This is why I say that although opting out of the system is attractive, some of the energy of a new generation of feminism dissipates because it is not anchored to any political structure. Can this energy coagulate into a single political entity?</p><p>Could we have a feminist party?</p><p>Liberal feminism is always critiqued for being too conciliatory and always compromised. It certainly feels like that at Westminster.</p><p>But while the media continues to tell us that recession produces only rightwing parties, in <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/may/20/first-mep-feminist-party-likely-win-seat-european-elections\" title=\"\">Sweden a feminist party</a> has risen up precisely out of anger about racism, the wage gap and male violence. It has only one MEP, but she is virulently anti-reactionary and taking on Sweden's \"wronged white men\".</p><p>A feminist party flags up the failure of traditional parties to change. For this fourth wave of feminism crashes against something prosaic. There is talk of mutiny, insurrection, revolution and it is glorious. But we need to create some new mechanisms of change that sustain themselves. The idea that recession produces only Ukip types is just not true. The fourth wave is firing imaginations: mine anyway. I imagine a party where all are welcome, where sparks fly, where the shifts in culture are properly reflected. Bring as many plus-ones and bottles as you like. It's time for My Big Fat Feminist Party.</p>","headline":"Harriet Harman is right about sexism in politics – let's start a feminist party","trailText":"<p><strong>Suzanne Moore: </strong>The fourth wave of feminism, from Caitlin Moran to Kimberlé Crenshaw, has energised young people, but now it needs to attack our political establishment</p>","newspaperPageNumber":"5","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"The Guardian","showInRelatedContent":"true","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/7/9/1404924523497/Harriet-Harman-006.jpg","wordcount":"895","commentable":"true","internalContentCode":"441673675","allowUgc":"false","internalOctopusCode":"9269356","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Suzanne Moore","newspaperEditionDate":"2014-07-10T00:00:00Z","internalPageCode":"2124009","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-07-12T19:00:00Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2014/jul/09/harriet-harman-sexism-politics-feminist-party","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/commentisfree/2014/jul/09/harriet-harman-sexism-politics-feminist-party","tags":[{"id":"commentisfree/commentisfree","webTitle":"Comment is free","type":"blog","sectionId":"commentisfree","sectionName":"Comment is free","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/commentisfree","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/commentisfree/commenti