 and powerful Labour deputy leader or the young man who sells his body for a living? It is certainly the latter, for all his perturbing aggression on that day. Yet in those very particular circumstances Harman seemed momentarily shorn of the protection of high social status and the young sex worker became briefly just another angry male jabbing a finger in a defenceless female's face. </p><p>But, of course, Harman is far from defenceless. Once the tirade was over she rebutted the incensed sex-worker's charges, dealing with him as doughtily as she dealt with stand-up comedy worker William Hague in the Commons on Wednesday. I say doughtily rather than brilliantly.  For me, she won the <a href=\"http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7923257.stm\">contest at the dispatch box</a> on points rather than by a knock out. Westminster specialists were split in their decisions: Harriet has that effect. </p><p>Even the Guardian's own couldn't agree. I think <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/blog/2009/mar/04/harman-hague-pmqs\">Nick Watt</a> is right that when she stuck it to Hague over his past enthusiasm for de-regulation she was stirring. She made her opponent look juvenile. Having her glasses on helped. <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/2009/mar/05/harriet-harman-prime-ministers-questions\">Simon Hoggart</a>, though, strikes me as half right in detecting a touch of primness: the quality that opens her up to \"posh lefty\" jibes. Elsewhere, the Indie's <a href=\"http://janemerrick.independentminds.livejournal.com/6511.html\">Jane Merrick</a> thought she edged it, while the Mail's Quentin Letts was predictably <a href=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/debate/article-1159489/QUENTIN-LETTS-The-young-shaver-did-best-laugh.html\">malicious</a>: he gets a kick out of pulling girls' hair. And here, perhaps, we approach the heart of it. With Harriet, it's all about sex. </p><p>Now, settle down. I do not mean that I fancy her rotten or think her all decoration and no depth. I mean that the particular style of femininity she personifies has a way of exciting conflicting passions. To a certain sort of Tory type – sometimes women included – the combination of a top-end middle class upbringing and left-ish, feminist views triggers a deep and quite alarming loathing. Letts is a classic example. Even a certain gentleman blond <a href=\"http://www.telegraph.co.uk/comment/columnists/borisjohnson/4929301/Mad-Hatties-raving-almost-made-me-think-of-siding-with-Sir-Fred.html\">succumbs</a> to a degree. It's as though in such circles it's not enough to disagree strongly with Harman. There is an urge to humiliate her too. For others, of course, she is a beacon of female achievement in a still bloke-centric world, a sister on the inside of patriarchy's citadel.</p><p>Me, I'm as divided within myself as are assessments of her generally. I've never met Harman, and so can't judge her as an individual. I will say, though, that affluent, liberal feminism (as opposed to the socialist variety I prefer) does tend to produce a certain kind of piety, one that sometimes forgets that a poor, ill-educated, life-damaged male is more disadvantaged than a poised, polished professional female. On Harman herself, I've felt at odds with her about gender politics and other sorts too. Sometimes, she just gets on my nerves. </p><p>Yet when she is targeted with a venom rarely deployed against male politicians guilty of things she's been accused of lately – high ambition, cunning, ineptitude – I instinctively taking her side. I don't know if it's \"progressive\" solidarity or old-fashioned gallantry, but whatever it is rebels against the nastiness and double-standards she inspires. And I can see that she is brave. Hague is the House wise guy, but she held her own. Is she prime minister material? A week ago I'd have said no immediately. Today, I'd have to give it a bit more thought.</p>","headline":"With Harriet, it's all about sex","trailText":"<p><strong>Dave Hill: 